<subSubSection id="C3146527FFD9E52A509887E1622EFEF5" pageId="24" pageNumber="141" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BB136ACFFD9E52A509887E1622EFEF5" blockId="24.[189,794,233,321]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">
<emphasis id="B97AEABEFFD9E52A509887E1623FFEB5" bold="true" box="[189,308,233,257]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Etymology</emphasis>
: The specific epithet is a composed adjective and alludes to the broad (latus) ventral process of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3146527FFD9E52A509886616619FCF5" pageId="24" pageNumber="141" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BB136ACFFD9E52A509886616121FC95" blockId="24.[189,794,361,2081]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">
<emphasis id="B97AEABEFFD9E52A509886616234FE35" bold="true" box="[189,319,361,385]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Description</emphasis>
: Body length 4.3–5.0 mm; length of forebody 
<quantity id="4CF69B49FFD9E52A509886816235FE15" box="[189,318,393,417]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.05" metricValueMax="2.2" metricValueMin="1.9" pageId="24" pageNumber="141" unit="mm" value="2.05" valueMax="2.2" valueMin="1.9">1.9–2.2 mm</quantity>
. Coloration (
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A51F28681612DFE15" box="[471,550,393,417]" captionStart="Figs 1–41" captionStartId="45.[151,191,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[152,1389,232,1855]" captionTargetId="figure-203@45.[151,1398,232,1874]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figs 1–41:Antennae of Zyrasspp.:kraatzi(1),exasperatus(2),pindarae (3–5),perforatus(6),championi(7),pallipes (8),condignus (9), nitens (10), truncatus (11), nilgiriensis (12), hirsutiventris (13), russiceps (14), brignolii (15), hastatus (16), parageminus (17–18), latilobatus (19), alternans (20), hirtus (21), nigroaeneus (22), luteipes (23), longilobatus (24), morvani (25), gratellus (Malaysia) (26), castaneus, lectotype (27),proximus (28–29),novinversus (30–31), brevilobatus(32), parvicollis(33), ambulans (34),matangensis (35), densissimus (36), densihirtus (37), nigrihirtus (38), gratellus (Sulawesi) (39), gardneri (40), titan (41). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742367/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Figs 19</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A521D8681615FFE15" box="[568,596,393,417]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">57</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A524086816189FE15" box="[613,642,393,417]" captionStart="Figs 82–99" captionStartId="53.[151,191,2018,2040]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-116@53.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="Figs 82–99: Abdomen of Zyras spp.: pindarae (82–85), perforatus (86), championi (87), pallipes (88), longilobatus (89), hastatus (90), truncatus (91), latilobatus (92), morvani (93), condignus (94), hirtus (95), gardneri (96), hirsutiventris (97), parageminus (98), alternans (99). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742383/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">92</figureCitation>
): head black; pronotum pale-reddish; elytra reddish-yellow with the postero-lateral portion more or less extensively blackish (sometimes leaving only the scutellum and its vicinity, the anterior margin, and the humeral angles reddish-yellow); abdomen bicoloured with tergites II–V pale-reddish, tergite VI pale-reddish with the middle and the posterior portion extensively blackish, tergite VII black with the anterior margin and the antero-lateral portions reddish, segment VIII black, and segments IX–X yellowish; legs yellowish; antennae reddish to brown with the basal and apical antennomeres more or less extensively palereddish; maxillary palpi yellowish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB136ACFFD9E52A509884216292FBD5" blockId="24.[189,794,361,2081]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">
Head (
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A512F8421625EFCF5" box="[266,341,809,833]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
) moderately transverse, median portion extensively impunctate; punctures in lateral portions rather sparse and fine. Eyes large, much longer than postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna (
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A52E284816019FC15" box="[711,786,905,929]" captionStart="Figs 1–41" captionStartId="45.[151,191,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[152,1389,232,1855]" captionTargetId="figure-203@45.[151,1398,232,1874]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figs 1–41:Antennae of Zyrasspp.:kraatzi(1),exasperatus(2),pindarae (3–5),perforatus(6),championi(7),pallipes (8),condignus (9), nitens (10), truncatus (11), nilgiriensis (12), hirsutiventris (13), russiceps (14), brignolii (15), hastatus (16), parageminus (17–18), latilobatus (19), alternans (20), hirtus (21), nigroaeneus (22), luteipes (23), longilobatus (24), morvani (25), gratellus (Malaysia) (26), castaneus, lectotype (27),proximus (28–29),novinversus (30–31), brevilobatus(32), parvicollis(33), ambulans (34),matangensis (35), densissimus (36), densihirtus (37), nigrihirtus (38), gratellus (Sulawesi) (39), gardneri (40), titan (41). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742367/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Fig. 19</figureCitation>
) conspicuously slender, approximately 
<quantity id="4CF69B49FFD9E52A525B84A161DBFC75" box="[638,720,937,961]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.9" pageId="24" pageNumber="141" unit="mm" value="1.9">1.9 mm</quantity>
long; antennomeres IV distinctly oblong, V–VIII decreasingly oblong, IX–X approximately as long as broad or weakly oblong, and XI elongate, approximately three times as long as broad and as long as the combined length of VIII–X, or nearly so.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB136ACFFD9E52A509883626212FA75" blockId="24.[189,794,361,2081]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A511F83616288FB35" box="[314,387,1129,1153]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
) slender, 1.04–1.07 times as broad as long and 1.1 times as broad as head, broadest near anterior angles; lateral margins straight (dorsal view); punctation not very coarse, rather dense, and regularly distributed, even along midline (i.e., median impunctate band absent). Elytra (
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A51328201626FFA95" box="[279,356,1289,1313]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
) approximately 0.8 times as long as pronotum; punctation rather fine and dense, and regularly distributed, only slightly less dense posteriorly than anteriorly. Hind wings fully developed. Metatarsomere I approximately as long as the combined length of II–IV.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB136ACFFD9E52A509882C16199F875" blockId="24.[189,794,361,2081]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">
Abdomen (
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A511E82C1628EFA55" box="[315,389,1481,1505]" captionStart="Figs 82–99" captionStartId="53.[151,191,2018,2040]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-116@53.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="Figs 82–99: Abdomen of Zyras spp.: pindarae (82–85), perforatus (86), championi (87), pallipes (88), longilobatus (89), hastatus (90), truncatus (91), latilobatus (92), morvani (93), condignus (94), hirtus (95), gardneri (96), hirsutiventris (97), parageminus (98), alternans (99). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742383/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Fig. 92</figureCitation>
) slightly narrower than elytra, with moderately deep anterior impressions on tergites III–V; anterior impressions of tergites III–V each with a transverse row of very coarse non-setiferous punctures; tergites III–IV with a lateral setiferous puncture on either side, and with four setiferous punctures at posterior margin; tergite V with a lateral setiferous puncture on either side, and with six setiferous punctures at posterior margin; tergites VI without non-setiferous punctation anteriorly, with a lateral setiferous puncture on either side, and with six setiferous punctures at posterior margin; tergite VII without non-setiferous punctation anteriorly, with two transverse series of fine setiferous punctures posteriorly, posterior margin with palisade fringe; tergite VIII (
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A52A7806161D2F835" box="[642,729,1897,1921]" captionStart="Figs 156–173" captionStartId="57.[151,191,2014,2036]" captionTargetBox="[154,1376,242,1969]" captionTargetId="figure-115@57.[151,1398,233,1972]" captionText="Figs 156–173: Zyras longilobatus (156–160), Z. latilobatus (161–165), Z. alternans (166–169), and Z. hirtus (170–173; 170–171: Sri Lanka; 172–173: South India): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (156–157, 161–162, 166–167, 170–173); paramere (158, 163); male tergite VIII (159, 164, 168); male sternite VIII (160, 165, 169). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888370" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888370/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Fig. 164</figureCitation>
) with setiferous punctures in posterior third, posterior margin smoothly convex, without median concavity.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB136ACFFD9E52A509880C26606FED5" blockId="24.[189,794,361,2081]" lastBlockId="24.[831,1437,233,354]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">
♂: sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A515480C162C2F855" box="[369,457,1993,2017]" captionStart="Figs 156–173" captionStartId="57.[151,191,2014,2036]" captionTargetBox="[154,1376,242,1969]" captionTargetId="figure-115@57.[151,1398,233,1972]" captionText="Figs 156–173: Zyras longilobatus (156–160), Z. latilobatus (161–165), Z. alternans (166–169), and Z. hirtus (170–173; 170–171: Sri Lanka; 172–173: South India): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (156–157, 161–162, 166–167, 170–173); paramere (158, 163); male tergite VIII (159, 164, 168); male sternite VIII (160, 165, 169). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888370" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888370/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Fig. 165</figureCitation>
) with convex posterior margin; median lobe of aedeagus (
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A51D180E1618FF7B5" box="[500,644,2025,2049]" captionStart="Figs 156–173" captionStartId="57.[151,191,2014,2036]" captionTargetBox="[154,1376,242,1969]" captionTargetId="figure-115@57.[151,1398,233,1972]" captionText="Figs 156–173: Zyras longilobatus (156–160), Z. latilobatus (161–165), Z. alternans (166–169), and Z. hirtus (170–173; 170–171: Sri Lanka; 172–173: South India): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (156–157, 161–162, 166–167, 170–173); paramere (158, 163); male tergite VIII (159, 164, 168); male sternite VIII (160, 165, 169). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888370" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888370/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Figs 161–162</figureCitation>
) of compact shape, approximately 
<quantity id="4CF69B49FFD9E52A51888F016100F795" box="[429,523,2057,2081]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="24" pageNumber="141" unit="mm" value="0.45">0.45 mm</quantity>
long; ventral process of distinctive shape, short, basally broad, apically acute in ventral view, and apically truncate in lateral view; paramere (
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A53A2862160D5FEF5" box="[903,990,297,321]" captionStart="Figs 156–173" captionStartId="57.[151,191,2014,2036]" captionTargetBox="[154,1376,242,1969]" captionTargetId="figure-115@57.[151,1398,233,1972]" captionText="Figs 156–173: Zyras longilobatus (156–160), Z. latilobatus (161–165), Z. alternans (166–169), and Z. hirtus (170–173; 170–171: Sri Lanka; 172–173: South India): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (156–157, 161–162, 166–167, 170–173); paramere (158, 163); male tergite VIII (159, 164, 168); male sternite VIII (160, 165, 169). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888370" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888370/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Fig. 163</figureCitation>
) slightly shorter than median lobe, with very short and apically truncate apical lobe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BB136ACFFD9E52A531A86816619FCF5" blockId="24.[831,1436,393,833]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">
<emphasis id="B97AEABEFFD9E52A531A8681672BFE15" bold="true" box="[831,1056,393,417]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E4D2FFFD9E52A541F868267F2FE15" authorityName="Assing" authorityYear="2017" box="[1082,1273,393,417]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latilobatus">
<emphasis id="B97AEABEFFD9E52A541F868267F2FE15" box="[1082,1273,393,417]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Zyras latilobatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other species of similar coloration by numerous characters, particularly the conspicuously slender and pale-coloured antennae, a slender pronotum without an impunctate median band, the presence of rather coarse non-setiferous punctation in the anterior impressions of tergites III–V, but absence of such punctation in the anterior portions of tergites VI–VII, a smoothly convex posterior margin of tergite VIII (without median concavity), and particularly the distinctive shape of the ventral process of the aedeagus. It is readily distinguished from the similarly coloured 
<taxonomicName id="4C0E4D2FFFD9E52A54F185E26642FCB5" authorityName="Fauvel" authorityYear="1904" box="[1236,1353,745,769]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="24" pageNumber="141" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hastatus">
<emphasis id="B97AEABEFFD9E52A54F185E26642FCB5" box="[1236,1353,745,769]" italics="true" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Z. hastatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, whose male sexual characters are unknown, by smaller size and especially by much more slender antennae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3146527FFD9E52A531A84616630FC15" pageId="24" pageNumber="141" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BB136ACFFD9E52A531A84616630FC15" blockId="24.[831,1436,873,930]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">
<emphasis id="B97AEABEFFD9E52A531A846160C3FC35" bold="true" box="[831,968,873,897]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Distribution</emphasis>
: This species is currently known only from the 
<typeStatus id="54B5880EFFD9E52A53428482609EFC16" box="[871,917,906,930]" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingRegion id="49CAF84EFFD9E52A542E84816759FC15" box="[1035,1106,905,929]" country="India" name="Kerala" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Kerala</collectingRegion>
, South 
<collectingCountry id="F319763CFFD9E52A5484848167D2FC15" box="[1185,1241,905,929]" name="India" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">India</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="13352A29FFD9E52A54C384816625FC15" box="[1254,1326,905,929]" captionStart="Map 7" captionStartId="67.[151,196,1246,1267]" captionTargetBox="[351,1198,232,1238]" captionTargetId="figure-79@67.[351,1198,232,1238]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="Map 7: Revised distributions of Zyras gardneri (black circles), Z. hirsutiventris (white diamonds), Z. parageminus (black triangles), Z. hastatus (white triangle), Z. hirtus (white circles), and Z. latilobatus (star) in India and adjacent regions." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742413" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742413/files/figure.png" pageId="24" pageNumber="141">Map 7</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
